==Latin==

===Etymology===
Back-formed from the accusative {{m|la|diem}}, at a time when the vowel was still long. From {{etyl|itc-pro|la}} {{m|itc-pro|*djēm}}, the accusative of {{m|itc-pro|*djous}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|la}} {{m|ine-pro|*dyew-||heaven, sky; to shine}}. The Italic stem was also the source of {{m|la|Iovis}}, the genitive of {{m|la|Iuppiter}}, and was generally interchangeable with it in earlier times (still shown by the analogical formation {{m|la|Diēspiter}}). The original nominative survives as {{m|la||*diūs}} in two fossilised phrases: {{m|la|mediusfidius|mē diūs fidius|pos=an interjection}} and {{m|la|nudiustertius|nū diūs tertius|day before yesterday|lit=now (is) the third day}}.

Cognate with Old Armenian {{term|տիւ||daytime|lang=xcl}}, Old Irish {{term|día|lang=sga}}, Welsh {{term|dydd|lang=cy}}, Polish {{term|dzień|lang=pl}}. English {{term|day|lang=en}} is a false cognate (see there).

===Pronunciation===
* {{la-pronunc|diēs}}

===Noun===
{{la-noun|diēs||diēī|m|g2=f|fifth}}

